<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="outcome-based-roadmaps">
  <metadata>
    <tier>solo</tier>
    <group>product</group>
    <domain>product-planning</domain>
    <summary>Commit to metric targets, not features. Each quarter: verb+metric+delta outcome, candidate solutions (to-validate), not-doing list. Solutions mutate; outcomes freeze.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>roadmap</tag>
      <tag>outcome-driven</tag>
      <tag>quarterly-planning</tag>
      <tag>metric-focused</tag>
      <tag>product-strategy</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-27</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Outcome-Based Roadmaps</title>

    <summary>An outcome-based roadmap replaces feature commitments with measurable metric targets as the unit of planning. Each quarterly slot carries a verb+metric+delta+timeframe outcome ("Reduce churn from 8% to 5% by Q2"), a list of candidate solutions marked "to-validate", and an explicit "not doing" list. Solutions are mutable mid-quarter; outcomes are frozen once set. This format keeps the roadmap valid across experiments and prevents stakeholders from treating it as a delivery contract.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Feature roadmaps commit to solutions before problems are validated. When a feature ships and fails to move the needle, the roadmap is wrong but the commitment is set. Outcome roadmaps shift the commitment to the goal—teams retain freedom to pivot solutions while preserving alignment on what success looks like. The format also surfaces planning slack: "Reduce support tickets by 30%" can be achieved by a chat feature, better docs, or a redesign—the roadmap survives any of those choices.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Quarterly planning where the best solution is still uncertain.</item>
        <item>Stakeholders conflate feature lists with contractual commitments.</item>
        <item>Discovery loop is active and the roadmap must survive the next experiment.</item>
        <item>Multiple teams or contractors need goal alignment without locking solutions.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Contractually committed deliverables (RFPs, enterprise SLAs, regulatory deadlines)—use a timeline roadmap.</item>
        <item>Pure execution phase with fully scoped and validated work—use a sprint/release plan.</item>
        <item>No metrics pipeline; outcome roadmaps require trustworthy baselines to be meaningful.</item>
        <item>Pre-PMF zero-to-one stage where finding any user is the priority, not moving a metric.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="outcome-roadmap-structure">
      <p>The anatomy of an outcome-based roadmap: outcome block format, contrast with feature roadmaps, and quarterly template structure.</p>

      <p>Feature vs Outcome Roadmap:</p>

      <p>A feature roadmap commits to solutions: "Build chat feature", "Add dark mode", "Launch mobile app". An outcome roadmap commits to metric movements: "Reduce support tickets by 30%", "Improve evening retention", "Enable on-the-go usage". The solution list under each outcome is marked "to-validate" and is mutable mid-quarter.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Every outcome must follow the pattern: verb + metric + delta + timeframe. Example: "Reduce churn from 8% to 5% by end of Q2." Outcomes missing any component are invalid.</statement>
        <rationale>The four-part pattern makes outcomes falsifiable. "Improve retention" cannot be scored at quarter-end; "Increase Day-30 retention from 20% to 35% by EOQ2" can.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <p>Outcome Block Anatomy:</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Each quarterly outcome block must contain: outcome statement (verb+metric+delta+timeframe), metric with baseline, target, evidence (data source or research), candidate solutions (3–6, all marked "to-validate"), and an explicit not-doing list (2–3 items).</statement>
        <rationale>The not-doing list is as important as the candidate solutions. It stops scope creep, sets stakeholder expectations, and creates a record for future retrospectives.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <p>Quarterly Structure:</p>

      <p>Q1 slot holds the outcome + experiments to run + metrics to track + potential solutions (not committed) + success criteria. Q2 slot follows the same structure. Each quarter is a frozen outcome with a mutable solution list. Outcomes are set at quarter boundaries; the solution list mutates as experiments resolve.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Cap quarterly outcomes at 3 for solo/small team, 5 for a team with multiple streams. More outcomes destroy focus; agents will pad to fill any number you allow.</statement>
        <rationale>Focus is the primary mechanism. Every additional outcome dilutes the attention and resources available for the others. Three well-executed outcomes beat five half-pursued ones.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="outcome-roadmap-rules">
      <p>Concrete rules for authoring, maintaining, and publishing outcome-based roadmaps, including agent-specific gotchas.</p>

      <p>Authoring Rules:</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Pair every outcome with a falsifying signal: "If activation drops below X by week 6, kill this bet." Without a kill signal, the outcome cannot be closed—teams keep pursuing it indefinitely.</statement>
        <rationale>Kill signals force honesty in retrospectives. An outcome without one will always find a reason to continue, burning resources that should pivot.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Tie every outcome to an existing analytics dashboard before publishing. If you cannot link a chart URL, the outcome is not yet real enough to plan around.</statement>
        <rationale>Outcomes anchored to real data prevent the common failure of setting targets without knowing the baseline. Agents will hallucinate plausible baselines—inject real data as context.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Maintain two publishing artefacts: an internal roadmap (outcomes + bets + targets) and an external/customer roadmap (themes and benefits only, no metric targets). Sync via script, not copy-paste.</statement>
        <rationale>Sharing metric targets externally creates contractual expectations. Customers interpret "reduce churn to 5%" as a promise; "improve retention" keeps strategic flexibility while communicating direction.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <p>Freeze and Mutation Rules:</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Keep outcomes immutable for the entire quarter. Only the candidate solutions list mutates as experiments resolve. Rewrite outcomes only at quarter boundaries.</statement>
        <rationale>Mid-quarter outcome changes invalidate all in-flight experiments and destroy the team's ability to measure progress. Solutions can pivot freely; the goal cannot.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Update cadence: review the solution list monthly, rewrite outcomes quarterly. Do not rewrite the whole document every sprint.</statement>
        <rationale>Over-frequent rewrites destroy the historical signal that makes retrospectives useful. Diffs between quarters are the primary learning artefact.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <p>Agent Gotchas:</p>

      <rule testable="false">
        <statement>When using an LLM to generate outcome roadmaps: require a metric + delta + verb in every outcome row, pull real baselines from analytics before prompting, clamp candidate solution lists to 6, and mark the not-doing field as required.</statement>
        <rationale>LLMs restate features as outcomes ("ship onboarding redesign" becomes "improve onboarding"), hallucinate numeric baselines, balloon solution lists, and silently drop the not-doing column because it produces no generative content.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="false">
        <statement>Never let an agent publish the external roadmap directly. Human checkpoint mandatory—outcome targets can be commitments; competitive and NDA implications require human review.</statement>
        <rationale>An LLM cannot assess business risk, NDAs, or competitive signalling context. These are human judgment calls.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="outcome-roadmap-antipatterns">
      <p>Five failure modes that undermine outcome-based roadmaps in practice.</p>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Vanity outcomes: "increase engagement", "delight users", "improve the platform".</description>
        <reason>Unmeasurable outcomes cannot be scored, kill-signalled, or retrospected. Teams pursue them indefinitely with no feedback loop. Apply the verb+metric+delta+timeframe test: if the outcome fails it, rewrite before planning.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Outcome inflation: every quarter declares 5+ outcomes, none get the sustained focus needed.</description>
        <reason>Each additional outcome divides attention and creates coordination overhead. Solo teams with 5 outcomes effectively have 5 equal priorities—indistinguishable from no priority. Cap at 3 for solo, 5 for small teams.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Disconnect from delivery: engineering runs a feature backlog and the outcome roadmap becomes a parallel document nobody trusts or references.</description>
        <reason>The roadmap becomes decoration unless initiatives in the backlog are tagged to outcome IDs. Without traceability, sprint planning ignores the roadmap entirely.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Confusing activities (inputs) with outcomes (metric movements): "run 5 user interviews" as an outcome.</description>
        <reason>Activities are means, not ends. A team can complete all activities and move no metrics. Outcomes must describe the metric state change, not the work done to achieve it.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Outcome roadmap weak with stakeholders who pay per feature; they push back unless they also receive a feature-derivative view.</description>
        <reason>Some audiences need feature language to understand what they are getting. Maintain the outcome roadmap internally; produce a feature-derivative or theme-only view for feature-oriented stakeholders.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/outcome-roadmap.md" purpose="Quarterly outcome roadmap: outcome blocks with metric, baseline, target, evidence, candidate solutions, not-doing"/>
      <template path="templates/lint-outcomes.py" purpose="Python validator: checks each outcome row for required fields and movement verb; fails CI if malformed"/>
    </templates>

    <see-also>
